The results of chemotaxis for fMLF are presented in Fig. 1C. Ferret PMNs showed no significant reaction with fMLF at any concentration or incubation time. Therefore, the binding between ferret neutrophils and formyl peptide were investigated using flow cytometry to determine the possibility of ferret FPR. The ferret PMNs expressed a complete lack of binding to formyl peptide at all concentrations tested (Fig. 2
), while human PMNs bound fluorescent-labeled formyl peptide at a concentration (10−10
 M) even lower than previously reported (Allen et al., 1992). FPR, one of the chemotaxis receptors that exists on human neutrophils, belongs to the GPCR (G protein-coupled receptor) family. Reports of a FPR binding assay using flow cytometry in human and pig neutrophils (Fletcher et al., 1990, Allen et al., 1992, Graves et al., 1992) found that human, but not porcine, neutrophils bind to the formyl peptide. Thus, the binding reaction to the formyl peptide appears to differ between species.
